---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Blockquote from '../../components/Blockquote.astro';

const usageSnippet = `---
import { Blockquote } from 'comet-astro';

---

<Blockquote
  author="Ada Lovelace"
  source="Notes on the Analytical Engine, 1843"
  variant="accent"
>
  That brain of mine is something more than merely mortal.
</Blockquote>`;
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Blockquote"
  description="Stylized quotations with optional author, source, and variants."
>
  <section class="space-y-4">
    <p class="text-base text-slate-100">
      Blockquotes spotlight testimony or citations while keeping long-form copy
      legible. Each variant maintains AAA contrast in both themes, pairing
      subtle italics with generous spacing.
    </p>
    <p class="text-base text-slate-200">
      Pair quotes with attribution metadata so readers immediately know who said
      what. When the source is omitted, the footer adapts automatically,
      preventing stray punctuation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 space-y-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">Props</h2>
    <dl class="grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <div
        class="space-y-1 rounded-lg border border-slate-700/75 bg-slate-900/60 p-4 shadow-sm"
      >
        <dt
          class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-200"
        >
          author?
        </dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-slate-200">
          Display name for the quoted speaker. Rendered within a semantic <code
            >cite</code
          > element.
        </dd>
      </div>
      <div
        class="space-y-1 rounded-lg border border-slate-700/75 bg-slate-900/60 p-4 shadow-sm"
      >
        <dt
          class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-200"
        >
          source?
        </dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-slate-200">
          Source or publication reference. Automatically prefixed with a comma
          when an author is supplied.
        </dd>
      </div>
      <div
        class="space-y-1 rounded-lg border border-slate-700/75 bg-slate-900/60 p-4 shadow-sm"
      >
        <dt
          class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-200"
        >
          variant?
        </dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-slate-200">
          Visual treatment: <code>default</code> for subtle, <code>accent</code>
          for emphasis, or <code>bordered</code> for card-style framing.
        </dd>
      </div>
      <div
        class="space-y-1 rounded-lg border border-slate-700/75 bg-slate-900/60 p-4 shadow-sm sm:col-span-2"
      >
        <dt
          class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-200"
        >
          className?
        </dt>
        <dd class="text-sm text-slate-200">
          Optional utility classes for layout tweaks—margins, max-widths, or
          typographic overrides.
        </dd>
      </div>
    </dl>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 space-y-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">Usage</h2>
    <p class="text-base text-slate-200">
      Import the component, provide your quote through the default slot, and set
      metadata props as needed. All variants respond to theme changes, so the
      default palette remains AAA-compliant without additional classes.
    </p>
    <pre
      class="overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-slate-700/70 bg-slate-950/80 p-4 text-sm text-slate-50 shadow-inner">
      <code class="language-astro">{usageSnippet}</code>
    </pre>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 space-y-8">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">Variants</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <Blockquote author="Grace Hopper">
        The most dangerous phrase in the language is, “We’ve always done it this
        way.”
      </Blockquote>
      <Blockquote
        author="Octavia Butler"
        source="Parable of the Talents, 1998"
        variant="accent"
      >
        Choose your leaders with wisdom and forethought.
      </Blockquote>
      <Blockquote
        variant="bordered"
        author="Frank Chimero"
        source="The Shape of Design"
      >
        People ignore design that ignores people.
      </Blockquote>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 space-y-4">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-100">Accessibility</h2>
    <p class="text-base text-slate-200">
      Italic styles remain modest to preserve legibility, and line height stays
      generous across screen sizes. Author attributions live inside <code
        >cite</code
      >, while the wrapper retains semantic <code>blockquote</code> markup so assistive
      tech understands the structure.
    </p>
    <p class="text-base text-slate-200">
      Add descriptive sources when available—notes like “Interview, 2024” or
      “Conference keynote” help readers anchor the quote. For extended
      commentary, continue within the slot so the quote and follow-up copy stay
      grouped visually and semantically.
    </p>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
